  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section firstReview">
      

<div id="review_605672170" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/605672170" />
    <a title="Sue Odenwelder" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14451626-sue-odenwelder"><img alt="Sue Odenwelder" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/605672170?book_show_action=true">May 02, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sue Odenwelder" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sue Odenwelder" href="/user/show/14451626-sue-odenwelder">Sue Odenwelder</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer605672170" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8752330551959278712">WOW! Where to begin? Carrie has done it again! I could actually feel the hurt &amp; pain Melody was experiencing. As a retired military wife, I so understand the loneliness &amp; isolation you feel when your husband is deployed in harms way. Add to that life &amp; death situations &amp; the isolation explodes into sheer panic, whether its your child or yourself. <br/><br/>I cried through this book, so that tells me I was pulled into the story &amp; felt the emotions of the characters - which is what a good author does. I cou</span>
  <span id="freeText8752330551959278712" style="display:none">WOW! Where to begin? Carrie has done it again! I could actually feel the hurt &amp; pain Melody was experiencing. As a retired military wife, I so understand the loneliness &amp; isolation you feel when your husband is deployed in harms way. Add to that life &amp; death situations &amp; the isolation explodes into sheer panic, whether its your child or yourself. <br /><br />I cried through this book, so that tells me I was pulled into the story &amp; felt the emotions of the characters - which is what a good author does. I could feel the hurt &amp; ask the same questions Melody asked. To me - the absolute worst thing that could ever happen is to lose a child, no matter the age, &amp; now that I am "Nana" to 5 beautiful grandchildren, that extends to them. <br /><br />Even though David was working through his own grief, he was a real source of strength for Melody - although that is not "written" it is a running theme throughout - with his gentleness, willingness to listen, his patience with Melody &amp; his great love for her. All these are qualities of a Godly man - for he had not given up on God - and I think that is why he was able to see Matthew &amp; Melody could not. <br /><br />I love that Carrie has Matthew in this series, because I truly believe God sends His angels to minister to us &amp; give us messages from God. And the way she interweaves Matthew in the lives of the characters gives them confirmation that he is indeed sent from God to them for a purpose. <br /><br />The best part was putting Melody with Faye.<br /> 1. Because she is a strong woman in her faith &amp; trust of God for all things. 2. Because Faye had also lost a child, Melody knew that Faye understood &amp; knew the pain &amp; hurt she was experiencing. When you go through such an event you don't want to listen to all the platitudes people say, but you will listen &amp; even grasp the words of one who have already walked the path you are now on. Because of this Melody listened to what Faye had to say about God &amp; His plan for our lives. Her mother &amp; aunt were too close &amp; had not lost a child, &amp; Melody shut them out. Good lesson for anyone counseling or knows someone needing counseling. Faye also reaffirmed to Melody that not all of what she was feeling was wrong, not even being angry with God.<br /><br />And finally, the word "Romancing". I was intrigued by the title before the book came out because we already knew Melody was married, but Carrie put a new spin on it - and I like it! I had never thought about God "romancing" us - but that is exactly what he does. Read about Esther - God "romanced" her "for such a time as this," &amp; she "romanced" the King to save the lives of the Jewish people. What awesome things does God have planned for our lives if we take time to listen for Him to speak to us?<br /><br />Carrie- it's an awesome book with lots of lessons. I look forward to "Crossing's Redemption"! Good luck with your move &amp; God bless you. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8752330551959278712" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


